1
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.000
She was born in Budapest in 1937. Her family called her Judit.

2
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:38.000
For one year of her life, in a convent on Stefánia Street, she was called Ilona.

3
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
She lives in Canada today. She is called Judy.

4
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:54.000
This is what one year of carrying two names can look like, in the words and geography of a real child who survived.

5
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Judit Grünfeld was born on April 28, 1937, to a Hungarian Jewish family in Budapest.

6
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Her parents, Renée and László, lived in the Pest district.

7
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Her mother used affectionate Hungarian nicknames for her: Jutka, Juditka. The kind of small, ordinary words a child carries through her whole life.

8
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:42.000
For seven years, this is who she was. A child in a city. A name her family used.

9
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:48.000
A grandmother. An aunt. Streets she knew by heart.

10
00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:00.000
In March 1944, German forces occupied Hungary.

11
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Within weeks the Hungarian government required all Jews aged six and older to wear the yellow star.

12
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:18.000
By mid-May, mass deportations of Hungarian Jews to Auschwitz had begun.

13
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:30.000
With the help of Mária Babar, a devout Catholic who had previously worked for the family,

14
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Judy's parents arranged for her to be hidden by the Ursuline nuns.

15
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Her father obtained forged identity papers in the name Ilona Papp.

16
00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:03.000
The convent was on Stefánia Street, near the Városliget city park.

17
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:13.000
The Ursuline Mother House. A working Catholic school with long stone corridors, classrooms, a chapel, dormitories.

18
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Judy was seven. She had to memorize a different life.

19
00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:30.000
Her name was now Ilona Papp. She was from a small village in the Hungarian countryside.

20
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Her parents were away during the war. She was Catholic. She knew Hail Mary and Our Father.

21
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:48.000
She did not know Yiddish. She did not know Hebrew. She did not know the names Judit, Jutka, or Juditka.

22
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:55.000
For almost a year, this was the cover.

23
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:05.000
The nuns ran the convent on a bell schedule. Prayer at fixed hours.

24
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Children walked in lines from dormitory to refectory to chapel. The Latin Mass was sung at sunrise.

25
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Beyond the convent walls, military trucks moved through the city.

26
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:32.000
In autumn 1944, as Allied bombing intensified, the Ursulines relocated Judy and other boarding students to Pincehely,

27
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:40.000
a small town in Tolna County in southwestern Hungary.

28
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:50.000
The displacement was brief but it removed her from the city at the most dangerous moment of the Hungarian deportations.

29
00:04:52.000 --> 00:05:01.000
On October 15, 1944, the Hungarian fascist Arrow Cross party took control of Budapest.

30
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Curfew sirens. Loudspeakers mounted on lamp posts broadcasting new orders. Snow was beginning.

31
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Judy was still Ilona in the village. She was still Judit when no one else was listening.

32
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Soviet forces liberated Pest on January 18, 1945.

33
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:36.000
Buda was liberated on February 13. Judy was reunited with her mother.

34
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Both of her parents survived. They had been deported to the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp as so-called exchange Jews,

35
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:57.000
held by the SS for possible ransom, and were liberated and reunited with Judy after the war.

36
00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:08.000
In 1949, the family emigrated to Montreal. Judy was twelve. She grew up in Canada.

37
00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:16.000
She became a French teacher at the United Nations International School in New York City.

38
00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:27.000
In 2011, the Azrieli Foundation Holocaust Survivor Memoirs Program published her memoir, Tenuous Threads.

39
00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
She was 74 years old.

40
00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:41.000
In 1994, Yad Vashem recognized Mária Babar, the family's caretaker who arranged Judy's hiding,

41
00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:47.000
as one of the Righteous Among the Nations.

42
00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:56.000
The names in Judy's story go forward, by the record, by name.

43
00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
Judit Grünfeld. Renée. László.

44
00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
Mária Babar. Ilona Papp, who kept her alive for almost a year.

45
00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Judy Abrams, who carried all of them into a memoir.

46
00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.000
Both kinds of carrying matter.
